<text top="3155" left="354" width="674" height="46" font="font9" id="p1_t30" reading_order_no="54" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">July  2007/Vol.  50,  No.7  COMMUNICATIONS  OF  THE  ACM</text>
<text top="1720" left="1250" width="961" height="63" font="font4" id="p1_t31" reading_order_no="28" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">senting  seven  Pittsburgh  Girl  Scout  troops.  They  cre-</text>
<text top="1773" left="1250" width="962" height="63" font="font4" id="p1_t32" reading_order_no="29" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">ated  their  storyboards,  as  well  as  their  programs,  in  a</text>
<text top="1824" left="1250" width="961" height="64" font="font4" id="p1_t33" reading_order_no="30" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">single  four-hour  session.  Participants  had  never  seen</text>
<text top="1876" left="1251" width="961" height="64" font="font4" id="p1_t34" reading_order_no="31" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">or  used  Storytelling  Alice  prior  to  the  user-testing  ses-</text>
<text top="1928" left="1250" width="960" height="65" font="font4" id="p1_t35" reading_order_no="32" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">sion.  On  average,  the  girls  in  the  study  spent  1-1.5</text>
<text top="1979" left="1251" width="962" height="64" font="font4" id="p1_t36" reading_order_no="33" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">hours  on  their  storyboards  and  2—2.5  hours  learning</text>
