<text top="2140" left="1250" width="711" height="57" font="font11" id="p1_t38" reading_order_no="35" segment_no="6" tag_type="title">3D  CHARACTERS  AND  OO  PROGRAMMING</text>
<text top="2188" left="1251" width="961" height="63" font="font4" id="p1_t39" reading_order_no="36" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">Storytelling  is  a  natural  way  to  introduce  the  basic</text>
<text top="2241" left="1250" width="959" height="65" font="font6" id="p1_t40" reading_order_no="37" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">concepts  behind  object-oriented  programming.</text>
<text top="2294" left="1250" width="960" height="65" font="font6" id="p1_t41" reading_order_no="38" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">Characters  are  reified  objects  that  know  how  to  per-</text>
<text top="2346" left="1250" width="960" height="65" font="font6" id="p1_t42" reading_order_no="39" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">form  a  variety  of  methods.  Objects  have  distinct  sets</text>
<text top="2405" left="1250" width="962" height="54" font="font3" id="p1_t43" reading_order_no="40" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">of  methods;  a  teacher  may  have  a  “scold  (character</text>
<text top="2456" left="1250" width="961" height="55" font="font1" id="p1_t44" reading_order_no="41" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">to  scold)”  method,  while  a  student  does  not.  One</text>
<text top="2502" left="1250" width="960" height="63" font="font4" id="p1_t45" reading_order_no="42" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">challenge  in  teaching  programming  to  beginning  pro-</text>
<text top="2555" left="1249" width="961" height="62" font="font2" id="p1_t46" reading_order_no="43" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">grammers  is  how  to  motivate  the  use  of  methods.  We</text>
<text top="2607" left="1250" width="959" height="62" font="font2" id="p1_t47" reading_order_no="44" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">found  that  the  need  for  multiple  scenes  in  stories  pro-</text>
<text top="2658" left="1249" width="960" height="63" font="font4" id="p1_t48" reading_order_no="45" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">vides  natural  motivation  to  use  methods.  The  girls  in</text>
<text top="2713" left="1250" width="961" height="62" font="font2" id="p1_t49" reading_order_no="46" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">the  study  wanted  to  be  able  to  work  on  the  action  for</text>
<text top="2765" left="1250" width="961" height="62" font="font2" id="p1_t50" reading_order_no="47" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">their  second  scene  without  having  to  watch  their</text>
<text top="2815" left="1250" width="960" height="65" font="font6" id="p1_t51" reading_order_no="48" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">entire  first  scene  in  order  to  do  so;  87%  of girls’  story-</text>
<text top="2869" left="1249" width="962" height="63" font="font4" id="p1_t52" reading_order_no="49" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">boards  included  multiple  scenes,  naturally  motivating</text>
<text top="2921" left="1250" width="959" height="62" font="font2" id="p1_t53" reading_order_no="50" segment_no="7" tag_type="text">the  use  of  methods.  Many  of  the  actions  study  partic-</text>
